  <page>
    <title>CNO cycle</title>
    <id>6061</id>
    <revision>
      <id>426273902</id>
      <timestamp>2011-04-27T21:08:28Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <username>USConsLib</username>
        <id>7855832</id>
      </contributor>
      <minor />
      <comment>/* Further reading */ Last name &quot;Iben&quot; not &quot;I.&quot;</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">[[Image:CNO Cycle.svg|300px|right|thumbnail|Overview of the CNO-I Cycle.]]

The '''CNO cycle''' (for [[carbon]]-[[nitrogen]]-[[oxygen]]), or sometimes '''Bethe-Weizsäcker-cycle''', is one of two sets of [[nuclear fusion|fusion]] [[nuclear reaction|reactions]] by which [[star]]s convert [[hydrogen]] to [[helium]], the other being the [[proton-proton chain]]. Unlike the proton-proton chain reaction, the CNO cycle is a [[catalytic cycle]]. Theoretical models show that the CNO cycle is the dominant source of energy in stars more massive  than about 1.3 times the mass of the [[sun]]. The proton-proton chain is more important in stars the mass of the sun or less. This difference stems from temperature dependency differences between the two reactions; pp-chain reactions start occurring at temperatures around {{val|4|e=6|ul=K}}, making it the dominant force in smaller stars. The CNO chain starts occurring at approximately {{val|13|e=6|u=K}}{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}, but its energy output rises much faster with increasing temperatures. At approximately {{val|17|e=6|u=K}}, the CNO cycle starts becoming the dominant source of energy.&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite journal
 | last=Schuler |first=S. C.
 | last2=King |first2=J. R.
 | last3=The |first3=L.-S.
 | year=2009
 | title=Stellar Nucleosynthesis in the Hyades Open Cluster
 | journal=[[The Astrophysical Journal]]
 | volume=701 | issue=1 | pages=837&amp;ndash;849
 | arxiv=0906.4812
 | bibcode=2009ApJ...701..837S
 | doi=10.1088/0004-637X/701/1/837
}}&lt;/ref&gt; The Sun has a core temperature of around {{val|15.7|e=6|u=K}} and only {{val|1.7|s=%}} of {{SimpleNuclide2|Helium|4|link=yes}} nuclei being produced in the Sun are born in the CNO cycle. The CNO process was independently proposed by [[Carl Friedrich von Weizsäcker|Carl von Weizsäcker]]&lt;ref&gt;
{{Cite journal
 |last=von Weizsäcker |first=C. F.
 |title=Über Elementumwandlungen in Innern der Sterne II
 |journal=[[Physikalische Zeitschrift]]
 |volume=39 |year=1938 |pages=633–46
}}&lt;/ref&gt; and [[Hans Bethe]]&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite journal
 |last=Bethe |first=H. A.
 |year=1939
 |title=Energy Production in Stars
 |journal=[[Physical Review]]
 |volume=55 |issue=5 |pages=434–56
 |bibcode=1939PhRv...55..434B
 |doi= 10.1103/PhysRev.55.434
}}&lt;/ref&gt; in 1938 and 1939, respectively.

In the CNO cycle, four [[proton]]s fuse, using carbon, nitrogen and oxygen isotopes as a catalyst, to produce one [[alpha particle]], two [[positron]]s and two electron [[neutrino]]s. The positrons will almost instantly [[Electron-positron annihilation|annihilate]] with electrons, releasing energy in the form of [[gamma ray]]s. The neutrinos escape from the star carrying away some energy. The carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen isotopes are in effect one nucleus that goes through a number of transformations in an endless loop.

== CNO-I ==
The main reactions of the CNO cycle are {{Nuclide2|carbon|12|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|nitrogen|13|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|carbon|13|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|nitrogen|14|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|oxygen|15|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|nitrogen|15|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|carbon|12}}:&lt;ref name=&quot;Krane&quot;&gt;
{{Cite book
 |last=Krane |first=K. S.
 |year=1988
 |title=Introductory Nuclear Physics
 |page=537
 |publisher=[[John Wiley &amp; Sons]]
 |isbn=0-471-80553-X
}}&lt;/ref&gt;
&lt;!-- Autogenerated using Phykiformulae 0.12 [[User:SkyLined#Phykiformulae]]
 C-12 + H -&gt; N-13 + y  _ _  + 1.95 MeV
 N-13 _ _ -&gt; C-13 + e+ + ve + 2.22 MeV
 C-13 + H -&gt; N-14 + y  _ _  + 7.54 MeV
 N-14 + H -&gt; O-15 + y  _ _  + 7.35 MeV
 O-15 _ _ -&gt; N-15 + e+ + ve + 2.75 MeV
 N-15 + H -&gt; C-12 + He _ _  + 4.96 MeV
--&gt;
:{| border=&quot;0&quot;
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|carbon|12}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|hydrogen|1}}&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|nitrogen|13}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|link=yes|Gamma}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||1.95&amp;nbsp;[[electron volt|MeV]]
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|nitrogen|13}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|carbon|13}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|link=yes|Positron}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|link=yes|Electron Neutrino}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||2.22&amp;nbsp;MeV
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|carbon|13}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|hydrogen|1}}&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|nitrogen|14}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Gamma}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||7.54&amp;nbsp;MeV
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|nitrogen|14}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|hydrogen|1}}&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|oxygen|15}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Gamma}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||7.35&amp;nbsp;MeV
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|oxygen|15}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|nitrogen|15}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Positron}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Electron Neutrino}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||2.75&amp;nbsp;MeV
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|nitrogen|15}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|hydrogen|1}}&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|carbon|12}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|helium|4}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||4.96&amp;nbsp;MeV
|}
where the Carbon-12 nucleus used in the first reaction is regenerated in the last reaction.

== CNO-II ==
In a minor branch of the reaction, occurring in the Sun's inner part, the core, just 0.04% of the time, the final reaction shown above does not produce carbon-12 and an alpha particle, but instead produces oxygen-16 and a photon and continues {{Nuclide2|nitrogen|15|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|oxygen|16|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|fluorine|17|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|oxygen|17|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|nitrogen|14|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|oxygen|15|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|nitrogen|15}}:

&lt;!-- Autogenerated using Phykiformulae 0.12 [[User:SkyLined#Phykiformulae]]
 N-15 + H -&gt; O-16 + y  _ _  + 12.13 MeV
 O-16 + H -&gt; F-17 + γ  _ _  + 0.60 MeV
 F-17 _ _ -&gt; O-17 + e+ + νe + 2.76 MeV
 O-17 + H -&gt; N-14 + He _ _  + 1.19 MeV
 N-14 + H -&gt; O-15 + y  _ _  + 7.35 MeV 
 O-15 _ _ -&gt; N-15 + e+ + ve + 2.75 MeV

--&gt;:{| border=&quot;0&quot;
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|nitrogen|15}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|hydrogen|1}}&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|oxygen|16}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Gamma}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||12.13&amp;nbsp;MeV
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|oxygen|16}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|hydrogen|1}}&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|fluorine|17}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Gamma}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||0.60&amp;nbsp;MeV
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|fluorine|17}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|oxygen|17}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Positron}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Electron Neutrino}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||2.76&amp;nbsp;MeV
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|oxygen|17}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|hydrogen|1}}&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|nitrogen|14}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|helium|4}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||1.19&amp;nbsp;MeV
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|nitrogen|14}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|hydrogen|1}}&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|oxygen|15}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Gamma}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||7.35&amp;nbsp;MeV
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|oxygen|15}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|nitrogen|15}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Positron}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Electron Neutrino}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||2.75&amp;nbsp;MeV
|}

Like the carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen involved in the main branch, the [[fluorine]] produced in the minor branch is merely catalytic and at steady state, does not accumulate in the star.

== OF Cycle ==
This subdominant branch is significant only for massive stars. The reactions are started when one of the reactions in CNO-II results in fluorine-18 and gamma instead of nitrogen-14 and alpha, and continues {{Nuclide2|oxygen|17|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|fluorine|18|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|oxygen|18|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|fluorine|19|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|oxygen|16|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|fluorine|17|link=yes}}→{{Nuclide2|oxygen|17}}:
&lt;!-- Autogenerated using Phykiformulae 0.12 [[User:SkyLined#Phykiformulae]]
 O-17 + H -&gt; F-18 + y  _ _  + 5.61MeV
 F-18 _ _ -&gt; O-18 + e+ + νe + 1.656MeV
 O-18 + H -&gt; F-19 + y  _ _  + 7.994MeV
 F-19 + H -&gt; O-16 + He _ _  + 8.114MeV
 O-16 + H -&gt; F-17 + y  _ _  + 0.60MeV
 F-17 _ _ -&gt; O-17 + e+ + ve + 2.76 MeV
--&gt;:{| border=&quot;0&quot;
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|oxygen|17}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|hydrogen|1}}&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|fluorine|18}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Gamma}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||5.61&amp;nbsp;MeV
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|fluorine|18}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|oxygen|18}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Positron}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Electron Neutrino}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||1.656&amp;nbsp;MeV
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|oxygen|18}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|hydrogen|1}}&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|fluorine|19}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Gamma}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||7.994&amp;nbsp;MeV
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|fluorine|19}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|hydrogen|1}}&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|oxygen|16}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|helium|4}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||8.114&amp;nbsp;MeV
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|oxygen|16}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|hydrogen|1}}&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|fluorine|17}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Gamma}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||0.60&amp;nbsp;MeV
|- style=&quot;height:2em;&quot;
|{{Nuclide2|fluorine|17}}&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||&amp;nbsp;||→&amp;nbsp;||{{Nuclide2|oxygen|17}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Positron}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||{{SubatomicParticle|Electron Neutrino}}&amp;nbsp;||+&amp;nbsp;||2.76&amp;nbsp;MeV
|}

Note that all these cycles have the same net result:
:4 {{Nuclide2|Hydrogen|1}} &amp;nbsp;→&amp;nbsp; {{Nuclide2|Helium|4}} &amp;nbsp;+&amp;nbsp; 2 {{SubatomicParticle|Positron}} &amp;nbsp;+&amp;nbsp; 2 {{SubatomicParticle|Electron neutrino}} &amp;nbsp;+&amp;nbsp; 3 {{SubatomicParticle|Gamma}} &amp;nbsp;+&amp;nbsp; 26.8 MeV

== Use in astronomy ==
While the total number of &quot;catalytic&quot; CNO nuclei is conserved in the cycle, in [[stellar evolution]] the relative proportions of the nuclei are altered.  When the cycle is run to equilibrium, the ratio of the carbon-12/carbon-13 nuclei is driven to 3.5, and nitrogen-14 becomes the most numerous nucleus, regardless of initial composition.  During a star's evolution, convective mixing episodes bring material in which the CNO cycle has operated from the star's interior to the surface, altering the observed composition of the star.  [[Red giant]] stars are observed to have lower carbon-12/carbon-13 and carbon-12/nitrogen-14 ratios than [[main sequence]] stars, which is considered to be convincing evidence for the operation of the CNO cycle.

The presence of the heavier elements carbon, nitrogen and oxygen places an upper bound of approximately 150 solar masses on the maximum size of massive stars. It is thought{{Who|date=May 2010}} that the &quot;[[Metallicity|metal]]-poor&quot; early universe could have had stars, called [[Metallicity#Population_III_stars|Population III stars]], up to 250 solar masses without interference from the CNO cycle at the beginning of their lifetime.

